The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Gargi Dasgupta, 28, a schoolteacher in Salt Lake, committed suicide by jumping from the roof of an 11-storeyed building in the Calcutta Police staff residential complex in AH block of the township. Police said Gargi, a divorcee, had been suffering from depression.

 Sixteen persons were injured after the Matador they were travelling in overturned on Rashbehari Avenue late on Monday. The Matador, carrying hilsa and lobsters, was coming from Diamond Harbour. Police said it overturned after the driver tried to avoid a car coming from the opposite direction. The injured were taken to hospital, where the condition of seven was critical.

 Ruhul Amin Khan, 30, was arrested when he was found loitering around CPM legislator Mursalin Mollah?s house in Akra Puratan Bazar, in Mahestala, on the southern fringes of the city, on Tuesday morning. A sharp weapon was found in his possession. Mollah, who was not at home, said his associates caught hold of Khan in front of his residence. He was later handed over to police. S.N. Gupta, superintendent of police, South 24-Parganas, said the youth was being interrogated.

 A 35-year-old man, identified as Naren Pal, was found murdered near Iswar Chowdhury Lane, in Khardah, on the northern fringes of the city, on Tuesday morning. Police said Pal might have been murdered elsewhere. The body has been sent for post-mortem. 

 The CID has arrested a 37-year-old man, Debashish Majhi, in Kharagpur for allegedly cheating a group of eight youths of around Rs 15 lakh. Sleuths said Majhi had promised the youths permanent jobs in the railway signal department. 

 he youths were sent on a six-month ?training? at various signal posts near Calcutta. On completion of the training, during which they were paid Rs 1,500 each as stipend, Majhi told the youths that they had failed the final test. Majhi was produced in court on Monday.

 Arpita Das, 32, was run over by a private bus on the Howrah-Domjur route near Panchanantala More, under Howrah police station, on Tuesday afternoon. Police said Das, a resident of Jhautala in Howrah, was travelling in a rickshaw that was hit from behind by the bus. Thrown off the rickshaw, she was mowed down by the rear wheels of the bus. The bus was impounded but the driver fled.

 Two persons were arrested by the anti-fraud squad of the commercial department of Eastern Railway during a drive on the Shipra Express on June 24. The two, Sudhir Rathi and wife Jayanti, were found to be travelling at concessional rates by producing fake papers that certified them as physically handicapped, officials said on Tuesday. The duo was later handed over to GRP.

 Alok Das, 34, a daily-wager, was critically injured after being crushed by a container filled with silk garments near Netaji Subhash Dock, under West Port police station, on Tuesday evening. Police said Das was admitted to SSKM Hospital.

 The AC three-tier and sleeper class coaches that were earlier attached to the Howrah-Danapur Express (3231 Up /3232 Dn) between Howrah and Madhupur will be tagged to the Calcutta-Delhi Lalquila Express (3111 Up / 3112 Dn) between Howrah and Madhupur from July 1. 

